    { "slug": "lake-forest", "name": "Lake Forest", "county": "Lake", "lat": 42.2586, "lng": -87.8406, "intro": "Lake Forest sits along Lake Michigan's bluffs in central Lake County, where ravines drain east toward the lake and large lots are shaded by mature oaks, maples, and elms. That landscape sets the tone for outdoor work here. Sprinkler systems contend with heavy clay-loam soils and pockets of poor drainage near the ravine edges — proper zone design and head spacing matter more than they do in newer subdivisions. We typically delay spring start-ups in Lake Forest until mid-to-late May because the lake-cooled air can hold overnight frost a few weeks past the inland counties.\n\nEstate properties around Onwentsia, Knollwood, and east of Sheridan Road are where landscape lighting carries the most weight: long driveways, gated entries, uplit specimen trees, and downlit terraces transform the night without overwhelming the architecture. Traditional holiday lighting on the Tudor and Georgian homes near Market Square is another seasonal staple. Bluestone walkways and clay-brick paver driveways — common throughout central Lake Forest — eventually need polymeric re-sanding and sealing, especially after the first decade of freeze–thaw. We've worked across all of these conditions for over 25 years." },
